(* ### Problem
 In regular pentagon $PQRST$, $X$ is the midpoint of segment $ST$. What is the measure of angle $XQS,$ in degrees?

[asy]
size(101);
picture p;
pair P = (0,0); pair Q = (-cos(108),sin(108)); pair R = Q + expi(36*pi/180); pair T = (1,0); pair S1 = T + (cos(108),sin(108));
draw(p,(P--Q--R--S1--T--cycle),linewidth(1)); pair X = (S1+T)/2;
label(p,rotate(20)*"$P$",P,rotate(20)*W,fontsize(10pt)); label(p,rotate(20)*"$Q$",Q,rotate(20)*NW,fontsize(10pt)); label(p,rotate(20)*"$R$",R,S,fontsize(10pt)); label(p,rotate(20)*"$S$",S1,rotate(20)*E,fontsize(10pt)); label(p,rotate(20)*"$T$",T,rotate(20)*N,fontsize(10pt));label(p,rotate(20)*"$X$",X,rotate(-40)*NE,fontsize(10pt));
dot(p,X);
add(rotate(-20)*p);
[/asy] The final Answer is 18^\circ
 ### Proof
 The measure of an interior angle in a regular pentagon is  $$\frac{180(5-2)}{5}=108^{\circ},$$ so $\angle QPT = 108^\circ$.
 From isosceles triangle $PQT$, we have $\angle PQT = (180^\circ - \angle QPT)/2 = 36^\circ$.
 Similarly, $\angle RQS = 36^\circ$. Finally, $\triangle SQT$ is isosceles with $SQ=QT$, so median $\overline{QX}$ is also an angle bisector of $\angle SQT$. Since $\angle SQT = \angle PQR - 36^\circ-36^\circ = 108^\circ-36^\circ-36^\circ = 36^\circ$, we have $\angle XQS = (\angle SQT)/2 = \boxed{18^\circ}$.
 *)

theorem
fixes XQS :: real
assumes h0 : "regular_polygon 5"
and h1 : "midpoint ST = X"
shows  "angle XQS = 18"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer

